{
  "doc_id": "22963",
  "text": "As the absolute phenylalanine concentration is the most crucial factor in directing treatment, phenylalanine measurements should be robust. The accuracy of aminoacid analysers, high-performance liquid chromatography, and tandem mass spectrometry is well established, but phenylalanine concentrations from dried blood spots are 8-26% lower than venous blood [CITATION_1] Bick et al (1993), [CITATION_2] Kono et al (2005), [CITATION_3] Cleary et al (1994), [CITATION_4] samples. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] Data from studies investigating neurocognitive outcomes are largely based on plasma phenylalanine concentrations, whereas routine practice is dried blood spots measurements. The guideline statements here on phenylalanine targets present the upper target phenylalanine concentrations, whereas the published work discusses means or medians. Consequently, the guideline statements are stricter than study fi ndings. However, this diff erence might also compensate for other factors, such as dried blood spots instead of plasma phenylalanine concentrations, and not testing blood phenylalanine after an overnight fast, which is usually the highest point in 24 h. [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] We advise that blood phenylalanine samples are taken at the same time of day and under the same nutritional conditions in each individual patient.",
